        "paragraph_index": 0,
        "text": "## Stability-Constant Measurements at 25 °C\n\n| Condition | Count | Percentage |\n|-----------|------:|----------:|\n| At 25 °C | 67,237 | **85.0%** |\n| All other temperatures | 11,826 | 15.0% |\n| **Total measurements** | **79,063** | **100%** |\n\n**85.0% of all stability-constant measurements in the NIST SRD-46 database were conducted at 25 °C.**\n\nThis overwhelming preference for 25 °C reflects the long-standing convention in solution thermodynamics of reporting equilibrium data at \"standard\" conditions (25 °C ≈ 298.15 K). The next most common temperatures are 20 °C (8.7%) and 37 °C (2.2%) — the latter corresponding to physiological temperature, important for biochemical and clinical chemistry studies. Together, just these three temperatures account for roughly 96% of all measurements in the database.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
